history.content:
We just heard from campus that we will not be able to get a bigger lecture hall for CS70 so that course will not expand and nobody who is not currently on the waitlist has any reasonable chance of being enrolled unfortunately.

It is more likely we will be able to expand 61C.  If the waitlist gets to 25, we will almost certainly do so and there is already room in the lecture hall so it would just be a matter of confirming a (U)GSI.

children.subject: "nobody who is not currently on the waitlist" implies those already on the waitlist should be fine I hope.

Unfortunately, that is not a logical inference.  A waitlist by definition means that one is not guaranteed a spot in the class. 

Attrition in summer classes happens but at a much lower rate than during the fall or spring semesters.  The waitlist has as many spots as it does because we had hoped to be able to find a larger lecture hall if demand warranted.  

Being # 11 or 13 is not hopeless but is far from guaranteed.
I'm #13 on the CS 70 waitlist. Do I have a reasonable change of getting in?
